    <h1>Quantifying NBA Player Value via Advanced Regression</h1>
    
    <div class="tldr">
        <strong>Project TL;DR:</strong> I built four iterations of offensive and defensive regression models to estimate Adjusted Plus-Minus. By engineering features like "Assisted Close Shots" and "Height-Adjusted Shot Blocking," I reduced residual error and identified why traditional box scores undervalue "connector" players like Steve Nash.
    </div>

    <h2>I. Offensive Modeling & Feature Engineering</h2>
    <p>Using play-by-play data (2005-2008), I moved beyond "Points" and "Assists" to model how specific play types impact team efficiency per 100 possessions.</p>

    <h3>Model 4: Final Offensive Estimate</h3>
    <div class="metric-box">
        <div class="metric">Mean Squared Residual: 11.96</div>
    </div>

    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Variable</th>
                <th>Coefficient</th>
                <th>Std. Error</th>
                <th>P-value</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr><td>Unassisted 3PT Made</td><td>2.986</td><td>0.410</td><td>&lt;.0001</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Assisted 3PT Made</td><td>2.199</td><td>0.199</td><td>&lt;.0001</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Assists on Close Shots</td><td>0.831</td><td>0.179</td><td>&lt;.0001</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Turnovers</td><td>-1.203</td><td>0.205</td><td>&lt;.0001</td></tr>
            <tr><td>True Shots * (Height - 60)</td><td>0.663</td><td>0.226</td><td>0.0034</td></tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Key Finding: The "Nash Effect"</h3>
    <p>Traditional models favored Amare Stoudemire (7.5) over Steve Nash (5.0). However, once the model accounted for <strong>Close Assists</strong> and <strong>Unassisted Shot Creation</strong>, Nash's value jumped to 8.4, aligning more closely with APM and his MVP-level impact.</p>

    <hr>

    <h2>II. Defensive Impact & Interaction Variables</h2>
    <p>Defense is notoriously difficult to capture in a box score. I hypothesized that defensive value is non-linear and depends heavily on physical profile and foul discipline.</p>

    <h3>Model 3: Final Defensive Estimate</h3>
    <div class="metric-box">
        <div class="metric">Mean Squared Residual: 11.59</div>
    </div>

    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Variable</th>
                <th>Coefficient</th>
                <th>Std. Error</th>
                <th>P-value</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr><td>Steals</td><td>1.768</td><td>0.230</td><td>&lt;.0001</td></tr>
            <tr><td>[Height - 60] * Blocks</td><td>0.088</td><td>0.015</td><td>&lt;.0001</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Shooting Fouls * Blocks</td><td>-0.427</td><td>0.109</td><td>&lt;.0001</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Charges Drawn</td><td>0.678</td><td>0.392</td><td>0.083</td></tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Observations on Defensive Latent Value</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Foul Interaction:</strong> I found that "Shooting Fouls * Blocks" is a significant negative predictor. This captures players who chase blocks but effectively put the opponent on the line, negating their rim protection value.</li>
        <li><strong>Physicality:</strong> Post players (like Chuck Hayes and Kevin Garnett) consistently show higher defensive ceilings in this model compared to perimeter defenders, suggesting a higher "floor" for interior disruption.</li>
    </ul>

